.SH NAME
Encode::CN \- China\-based Chinese Encodings
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 3
\&    use Encode qw/encode decode/; 
\&    $euc_cn = encode("euc\-cn", $utf8);   # loads Encode::CN implicitly
\&    $utf8   = decode("euc\-cn", $euc_cn); # ditto
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module implements China-based Chinese charset encodings.
Encodings supported are as follows.
.PP
.Vb 10
\&  Canonical   Alias             Description
\&  \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&  euc\-cn      /\ebeuc.*cn$/i     EUC (Extended Unix Character)
\&          /\ebcn.*euc$/i
\&              /\ebGB[\-_ ]?2312(?:\eD.*$|$)/i (see below)
\&  gb2312\-raw                    The raw (low\-bit) GB2312 character map
\&  gb12345\-raw                   Traditional chinese counterpart to 
\&                GB2312 (raw)
\&  iso\-ir\-165                    GB2312 + GB6345 + GB8565 + additions
\&  MacChineseSimp                GB2312 + Apple Additions
\&  cp936                         Code Page 936, also known as GBK 
\&                (Extended GuoBiao)
\&  hz                            7\-bit escaped GB2312 encoding
\&  \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
.Ve
.PP
To find how to use this module in detail, see Encode.
.SH NOTES
.IX Header "NOTES"
Due to size concerns, \f(CW\*(C`GB 18030\*(C'\fR (an extension to \f(CW\*(C`GBK\*(C'\fR) is distributed
separately on CPAN, under the name Encode::HanExtra. That module
also contains extra Taiwan-based encodings.
.SH BUGS
.IX Header "BUGS"
When you see \f(CW\*(C`charset=gb2312\*(C'\fR on mails and web pages, they really
mean \f(CW\*(C`euc\-cn\*(C'\fR encodings.  To fix that, \f(CW\*(C`gb2312\*(C'\fR is aliased to \f(CW\*(C`euc\-cn\*(C'\fR.
Use \f(CW\*(C`gb2312\-raw\*(C'\fR when you really mean it.
.PP
The ASCII region (0x00\-0x7f) is preserved for all encodings, even though
this conflicts with mappings by the Unicode Consortium.
